    {
      "text": "A 28-year-old male presents to the emergency department 10 days after sustaining blunt trauma to the face during a basketball game. He complains of diplopia and difficulty moving his left eye upwards. On examination, there is significant periorbital swelling. The X-ray is shown below. What does this X-ray indicate in this patient, and what is the most appropriate next step in management?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "Orbital fat herniation; apply ice and prescribe analgesics"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Orbital floor fracture; surgical evaluation"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Orbital haemorrhage; immediate CT scan"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Maxillary sinus fracture; follow-up with ENT specialist"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 1,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct answer: B) <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"bfe6beb7131692777194500ac5f2d2\">Orbital</span> floor fracture; <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"81d12f9cb01692777199e44ff3f3c1\">surgical</span> evaluation</strong></p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation: </strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>The \"<strong>teardrop sign\" or “hanging drop sign</strong>” on the X-ray suggests an <strong>orbital floor</strong> <strong>fracture</strong>, often associated with muscle entrapment, which leads to restricted eye movement and diplopia.</li>\n\t<li>The appropriate next step in management would be to evaluate for <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"81d12f9cb01692777199e44ff3f3c1\">surgical</span> intervention to relieve the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"025e317c8116927771870f34a94b56\">entrapment</span> and repair the fracture.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>Orbital floor <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"e3727bc4841692777203d62242b6e6\">fracture</span> (also known as blow-out fracture): </strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>A blow-out <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"e3727bc4841692777203d62242b6e6\">fracture</span> usually occurs due to a sudden rise in <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"bfe6beb7131692777194500ac5f2d2\">orbital</span> pressure from an impacting object, like a fist or tennis ball, causing the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"53c6bebcbb169277718777b3fe0e5c\">eyeball</span> to be displaced and transmit, rather than absorb, the impact.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>Classification</strong>:</p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>Pure blow-out fractures are isolated to the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"bfe6beb7131692777194500ac5f2d2\">orbital</span> walls (floor or <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"db46007ad21692777192dcc160a2e2\">medial</span> wall) without involving the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"bfe6beb7131692777194500ac5f2d2\">orbital</span> rim.</li>\n\t<li>Impure blow-out fractures involve the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"bfe6beb7131692777194500ac5f2d2\">orbital</span> walls, the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"bfe6beb7131692777194500ac5f2d2\">orbital</span> rim, and surrounding <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"9fdd7489051692777202cffe3f24cc\">facial</span> bones.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>Clinical features: </strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>Periorbital oedema and blood <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"f0c6fefae41692777187c76a6f65f6\">extravasation</span> in and around the orbit (such as <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"335f16a33c16927771992f5c55bc4d\">subconjunctival</span> ecchymosis)</li>\n\t<li>Emphysema (subcutaneous) of the eyelids</li>\n\t<li>Paraesthesia and anaesthesia in the distribution of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"6c3d094a46169277719011ea38746a\">infraorbital</span> nerve (lower lid, cheek, side of nose, upper lip, and upper teeth).</li>\n\t<li>Ipsilateral <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"26bb4e3cc81692777187ce44e530e5\">epistaxis</span> (bleeding from maxillary sinus)</li>\n\t<li>Proptosis (orbital oedema and haemorrhage).</li>\n\t<li>Enophthalmos and mechanical ptosis</li>\n\t<li>Diplopia (oedema, haemorrhage, <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"025e317c8116927771870f34a94b56\">entrapment</span> of muscle (inferior rectus/inferior oblique) at the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"e3727bc4841692777203d62242b6e6\">fracture</span> site.</li>\n\t<li><strong>Hess chart testing</strong> (map eye movements for assessment and monitoring).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img alt=\"-\" data-author=\"McBride, Geraldine. \" data-hash=\"1965\" data-license=\"CC BY\" data-source=\"https://www.researchgate.net/figure/Hess-chart-on-the-first-orthoptic-visit-showing-left-hyperdeviation-in-all-positions-of_fig1_323937778\" data-tags=\"March2025\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/notes/kNeRJJvIMNLIfC2NIUoI1742990022.png\" /></p>\n\n<p><strong>Orbital imaging: </strong></p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>X-rays: A nose-chin (Water's) view showing '<strong>hanging drop</strong>' <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"a8eadab50316927771948be0cc91ca\">opacity</span> of the superior maxillary <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"96976bc5fc1692777181dc8403015a\">antrum</span> from <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"bfe6beb7131692777194500ac5f2d2\">orbital</span> contents herniating through the floor.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img alt=\"-\" data-author=\"Cobb, A. R., Murthy, R., Saiet, J., Bailey, B., & Hibbert, J.\" data-hash=\"1958\" data-license=\"NA\" data-source=\"https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0266435608000417\" data-tags=\"March2025\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/notes/Do8VedIl8s31OGogUBT41742990018.png\" /></p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Plain X-ray orbit (AP view) showing <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"18b73c28601692777188f2aae28838\">herniated</span> <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"bfe6beb7131692777194500ac5f2d2\">orbital</span> contents (arrow) with blow-out <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"e3727bc4841692777203d62242b6e6\">fracture</span> of the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"bfe6beb7131692777194500ac5f2d2\">orbital</span> floor</p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>Computerised <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"8d4f2a375b1692777200f41db641bc\">tomography</span> (CT) <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"c497b556951692777198b599e4ba86\">scanning</span> and magnetic <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"37b9856df8169277719716b550a15f\">resonance</span> imaging(MRI): Evaluate the extent of the <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"e3727bc4841692777203d62242b6e6\">fracture</span> and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"7133d43878169277718890fcb091d5\">herniation</span> of contents into maxillary <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"96976bc5fc1692777181dc8403015a\">antrum</span> <strong>(hanging drop or tear drop sign).</strong></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:center\"><img alt=\"-\" data-author=\"Gooris, Peter & Mourits, Maarten & Mensink, Gertjan & Bergsma, Jan.\" data-hash=\"1959\" data-license=\"CC BY 4.0\" data-source=\"https://www.researchgate.net/figure/Teardrop-sign-as-a-result-of-an-orbital-floor-trapdoor-fracture-OS-coronal-view_fig4_376932263\" data-tags=\"March2025\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/notes/MUqzEISWAeczslBTxmQR1742990018.png\" /></p>\n\n<p style=\"text-align:center\">CT scan of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"dad5b2152216927771851a3d10cd41\">coronal</span> section of orbit showing <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"e3727bc4841692777203d62242b6e6\">fracture</span> floor with <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"7133d43878169277718890fcb091d5\">herniation</span> of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"bfe6beb7131692777194500ac5f2d2\">orbital</span> contents</p>\n\n<p> </p>\n\n<p><strong>Management: </strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>Antibiotics and anti-inflammatory drugs</li>\n\t<li>Ice packs and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"31c5d0e75f16927771938d8e2daa4c\">nasal</span> decongestants</li>\n\t<li>Surgery (dislodge the muscle and do microplating)\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li><strong>Indications for surgery:</strong>\n\t\t<ul>\n\t\t\t<li>No improvement in <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"1458c330411692777186cd49bb6a30\">diplopia</span> or <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"1f51f462bc1692777187ffc9d3094b\">enophthalmos</span> even after 10 days (indicates muscle entrapment).</li>\n\t\t\t<li>Enopthalmos is > 2mm</li>\n\t\t\t<li>Half of the floor is fractured</li>\n\t\t</ul>\n\t\t</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p> </p>",
